'''Arthur Frederic Basil Williams''' {{Post-nominals|post-noms=[[OBE]]}} (4 April 1867 – 5 January 1950) was an [[England|English]] [[historian]]. 

Williams was born in [[London]], the son of a [[barrister]].  He was educated at [[Marlborough College]] and then read Classics at [[New College, Oxford]]. He was a clerk in the House of Commons. One of his duties was to attend the parliamentary committee of inquiry into the responsibility for the [[Jameson raid]], and he became familiar with [[Cecil Rhodes]], whose biography he later wrote. 

Williams served in the [[Second Boer War]], where one of his companions was [[Robert Erskine Childers|Erskine Childers]], of whom he later wrote a memoir.<ref>{{cite book|last=Williams|first=Basil|authorlink= Basil Williams (historian)|title=Erskine Childers, 1870–1922: A Sketch|publisher=Privately published—Molly Childers|year=1926|location= London|url=|id=|oclc=34705727}}</ref>  In 1905 he married Dorothy Caulfeild{{sic}}. She died two years before him.<ref name=ODNB/>

Williams came back to the UK briefly, then returned to South Africa as a civilian, in the service of [[Lord Milner]]. He also worked as an assistant to Lionel Curtis, the town clerk of [[Johannesburg]]. In 1910 he was twice unsuccessful in [[Prospective parliamentary candidate|UK parliamentary elections]] standing in the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] interest, in turn for the seats of [[Lewes (UK Parliament constituency)|Lewes]] and [[Rugby (UK Parliament constituency)|Rugby]]. During [[World War I]], he served as an education officer in the [[Royal Field Artillery]] and in 1919 was awarded the OBE for his services.<ref name=ODNB>{{cite book|last1=Pares|first1=Richard|last2=Matthew|first2=H. C. G.|title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|date=25 May 2006|doi=|chapter=Williams, (Arthur Frederic) Basil}}</ref>

Williams had already made an impression as an academic, with a series of articles on Sir [[Robert Walpole]]'s foreign policy in the ''English Historical Review'' (1900&ndash;1). He became Kingsford Professor of History at [[McGill University]] in 1921, and then professor of History at [[Edinburgh University]] from 1925 to 1937 when he retired. In 1935 he was elected a fellow of the British Academy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Professor (Arthur Frederick) Basil Williams {{!}} British Academy|url=https://www.britac.ac.uk/fellows/professor-arthur-frederick-basil-williams|website=British Academy|accessdate=11 May 2018|language=en}}</ref> He wrote biographies of [[William Pitt, Earl of Chatham]] (1913), and Stanhope (1932), [[John Carteret, 2nd Earl Granville|Carteret]] and [[Thomas Pelham-Holles, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Newcastle]] (1943). He retained his interest in South Africa, and this became a secondary sphere of historical interest. In 1946 he produced a book on [[Louis Botha|Botha]], [[Louis Botha|Smuts]] and South Africa. He also contributed a volume entitled ''The Whig Supremacy'' to the ''[[Oxford History of England]]'', later updated by [[C. H. Stuart]].<ref>{{ISBN| 9780198217107 }}</ref>
