{{Paranormal}} '''Etzel Cardeña''' (born November 9, 1957)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n99834633.html |title=Cardeña, Etzel |website=Library of Congress Name Authority File |access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref> is the Thorsen Professor of Psychology at [[Lund University]], Sweden<ref name=wood>{{citation|url=https://universitetslararen.se/2006/01/01/professor-i-parapsykologi-soker-latthypnotiserade/|language=Swedish|title=Professor i parapsykologi söker lätthypnotiserade|newspaper=Universitetsläraren|date=January 1, 2006|first=Anki|last=Wood}}</ref> where he is Director of the Centre for Research on Consciousness and Anomalous Psychology (CERCAP). He has served as President of the Society of Psychological Hypnosis,<ref name=div30>{{citation|url=http://www.apadivisions.org/division-30/leadership/past-presidents/index.aspx|title=Past Presidents|publisher=American Psychological Association Division 30: Society of Psychological Hypnosis|accessdate=2018-09-09}}</ref> and the Society for Clinical and Experimental Hypnosis.<ref name=sceh>{{citation|url=http://www.sceh.us/assets/scehpartpresidentslistofficial2017.pdf|title=SCEH Past Presidents|year=2017|publisher=Society for Clinical and Experimental Hypnosis|accessdate=2018-09-09}}</ref> He is the current editor of the ''[[Journal of Parapsychology]]''.<ref name=jpara>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rhine.org/resources/journal-of-parapsychology/journal-of-parapsychology-current-issue/313-editors-and-editorial-review-board.html |title=Editors and Editorial Review Board |publisher=Rhine Research Center |journal=Journal of Parapsychology |access-date=2018-01-21}}</ref> He has expressed views in favour of open scientific enquiry and the validity of some [[paranormal]] phenomena.<ref name=wood/><ref>{{citation|language=Swedish|title=Lundaprofessorn som jagar bevis för tankeöverföring|newspaper=Svenska Dagsbladet|url=https://www.svd.se/lundaprofessorn-som-jagar-bevis-for-tankeoverforing}}</ref><ref>{{citation|language=Swedish|url=https://www.svd.se/pseudovetenskap-sprids-okritiskt|newspaper=Svenska Dagsbladet|title=Pseudovetenskap sprids okritiskt}}</ref> The [[Parapsychological Association]] honored Cardena with the 2013 [[Charles Honorton]] Integrative Contributions Award.<ref name=honorton>{{citation|url=https://www.parapsych.org/articles/31/181/2013_charles_honorton_integrative.aspx|publisher=[[Parapsychological Association]]|title=2013 Charles Honorton Integrative Contributions Award Winner: Etzel Cardeña|year=2013|accessdate=2018-09-09}}</ref> His publications include the books ''Altering Consciousness''<ref name=altcon>Reviews of ''Altering Consciousness'': *{{citation|last=Hastings|first=Arthur|issue=1|journal=Journal of Transpersonal Psychology|pages=100–103|title=Review|url=https://search.proquest.com/openview/77de73b3700cbdf6887f1d5c028d09df/1|volume=44|year=2012}} *{{citation|last=Smith|first=Frederick M.|date=June 2012|doi=10.1111/j.1748-0922.2012.01593.x|issue=2|journal=Religious Studies Review|pages=70–70|title=none|volume=38}}</ref> and ''[[Varieties of Anomalous Experience]]''.<ref name=vae>Reviews of ''Varieties of Anomalous Experience'': *{{citation|last=Rich|first=Grant Jewell|date=March 2001|issue=1|journal=American Anthropologist|jstor=683986|pages=266–267|title=none|volume=103}} *{{citation|last=Schroll|first=Mark A.|date=September 2001|doi=10.1525/ac.2001.12.2.63|issue=2|journal=Anthropology of Consciousness|pages=63–65|title=none|volume=12}} *{{citation|last=Hood|first=Ralph W.|date=March 2014|doi=10.1080/10508619.2014.900413|issue=2|journal=The International Journal for the Psychology of Religion|pages=170–172|title=none|volume=25}}</ref>
==History== Etzel Cardeña is the Thorsen Professor of Psychology (including [[parapsychology]] and [[hypnosis]]) at [[Lund University]], Sweden where he is Director of the Centre for Research on Consciousness and Anomalous Psychology (CERCAP). A native of [[Mexico]], Cardeña studied at the [[Universidad Iberoamericana]] in México and completed an MA in clinical psychology at York University in Toronto, Canada and an MA and PhD in Personality Psychology at the [[University of California, Davis]]. His doctoral thesis under the supervision of [[Charles Tart]] was on the phenomenology of deep states of hypnosis. He subsequently went on to do post-doctoral work in the area of [[dissociation (psychology)|dissociation]] and [[hypnosis]] at [[Stanford University]] under [[David Spiegel]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parapsych.org/members/e_cardena.html |title=Edzel Cardena |publisher=Parapsych.org |date= |accessdate=2012-11-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100927201411/http://parapsych.org/members/e_cardena.html |archive-date=2010-09-27 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> Cardeña has held academic posts at Georgetown University, the [[Uniformed Services University of the Health Sciences]] (USUHS) and the [[University of Texas–Pan American]], among others. He has served as President of the Society of Psychological Hypnosis (APA Division 30) for 2000–2001,<ref name=div30/> the Society for Clinical and Experimental Hypnosis for 2001–2003,<ref name=sceh/> and the [[Parapsychological Association]] for the year 2008-2009. He has expressed views in favour of the validity of some [[paranormal]] phenomena. In a recent paper in [[American Psychologist]] he wrote that "The evidence for psi is comparable to that for established phenomena in psychology and other disciplines, although there is no consensual understanding of them."<ref>Cardeña, E. (2018). The experimental evidence for parapsychological phenomena: A review. American Psychologist, 73(5), 663-677.</ref>
In a series of interviews with Swedish Newspapers he has said that there is evidence for [[telepathy]], [[psychokinesis]] and [[precognition]] and that he himself has had experiences that could be interpreted as supporting the psi hypothesis.<ref>[http://www.salongk.se/artiklar/import/2006/9/7/4470/index.xml ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930214511/http://www.salongk.se/artiklar/import/2006/9/7/4470/index.xml |date=September 30, 2011 }}</ref> The [[Parapsychological Association]] honored Cardena with the 2013 [[Charles Honorton]] Integrative Contributions Award.<ref name=honorton/> Cardena has written more than 300 publications. His edited book ''[[Varieties of Anomalous Experience]]: Examining the Scientific Evidence'' published in 2000 and a second edition in 2014 is a scholarly volume on anomalous experiences.<ref name=vae/> His two volumes ''Altering Consciousness'' discusses the importance of altered states across history, culture, and in many disciplines including philosophy, anthropology, psychology, biology, and various others.<ref name=altcon/>
In addition to his professional work in psychology Etzel Cardeña is the Artistic Director of the International Theatre of Malmö and has worked in theatre as a director, actor and playwright in Mexico, the USA and Sweden. He did graduate studies in theatre directing at the [[University of California, Davis]], after having worked professionally in theatre in México<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.internationaltheatremalmo.se/creative_team.html|title=Creative team|publisher=International Theatre of Malmö|accessdate=2018-09-09}}</ref> and been offered scholarships from the Polish and Canadian governments to do graduate work in acting.
==Publications== Scientific publications include more than 250 journal articles and book chapters in journals such as ''[[Annual Review of Clinical Psychology]]'', ''[[American Journal of Psychiatry]]'', ''[[Journal of Abnormal Psychology]]'', ''[[Archives of General Psychiatry]],'' and ''Cortex,'' and the following books: * Kirsch, I., Capafons, A., Cardeña, E., & Amigó, S. (Eds.) (1999). ''Clinical hypnosis and self-regulation therapy: A cognitive-behavioral perspective''. Washington, DC: American Psychological Association. * Cardeña, E., Lynn, S. J., & Krippner, S. (Eds.). (2000). ''[[Varieties of Anomalous Experience]]: Examining the scientific evidence''. Washington, DC: American Psychological Association. 2nd ed. (2014) Washington, DC: American Psychological Association.<ref name=vae/> * Cardeña, E., & Croyle, K. (Eds.) (2005). ''Acute reactions to trauma and psychotherapy: A multidisciplinary and international perspective''. New York: Haworth Press. Also published as special issue of the Journal of Trauma and Dissociation, 6(2).<ref>Reviews of ''Acute reactions to trauma and psychotherapy'': *{{citation|last=Beecher|first=Elke|date=May 2007|doi=10.1080/13229400.2007.11003964|issue=1|journal=Journal of Family Studies|pages=115–116|title=none|volume=13}} *{{citation|last=Gravitz|first=Melvin A.|date=January 2009|doi=10.1080/00029157.2009.10401679|issue=3|journal=American Journal of Clinical Hypnosis|pages=299–300|title=none|volume=51}}</ref> * Cardeña, E., & Winkelman, M. (2011). Altering consciousness. Multidisciplinary perspectives. Volume I. History, culture, and the humanities; Volume II. Biological and psychological perspectives. Santa Barbara, CA: Praeger Publishers.<ref name=altcon/>
