'''Ida Silverman''' (31 October 1882 – 1 November 1973) was a Jewish philanthropist, who with her husband helped found approximately 100 [[synagogue]]s, mostly in Israel. She is the only woman to have served as vice president of the [[Zionist Organization of America]] and the [[American Jewish Congress]].

A Russian immigrant, Silverman arrived in the United States before she was a year old. Her family settled in [[Providence, Rhode Island]], where she completed her schooling, married and had four children. While doing relief work during the [[World War I|First World War]], she became aware of the depth of social problems and the effects of war on refugees. Joining the [[Zionist]] movement in the 1900s, within a decade she became a motivational speaker, advocating for the establishment of a permanent Jewish home in Palestine.

Between 1925 and the late 1940s, she logged over 600,000 air-miles traveling throughout the world, speaking and fund raising for the creation of a [[Jewish state]]. Even during [[World War II]], she received special permission to travel into war-torn areas to evaluate conditions. At the war's end, Silverman turned her efforts toward building infrastructure in the new nation of Israel, but was also involved in philanthropy in her home state of Rhode Island, raising funds for hospitals and mental health organizations.

She received many honors and awards for her philanthropy including Jewish Mother of the Year, the Mizrachi Women's Organization of America's "Silver Medal" for building Israel, honorary doctorates, and jointly with her husband was inducted into the [[Rhode Island Heritage Hall of Fame Women Inductees|Rhode Island Heritage Hall of Fame]] in 1971.

==Biography==
Ida Marcia Camelhor was born on 31 October 1882 in [[Kovno Governorate|Kovno, Russia]] to Mary (née Dember) and Louis Camelhor{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1973|p=480}} (also noted as Lieb Kamelhorn). She was the only surviving child of a family of eight.<ref name="alternate name spelling">{{cite news|title=Well-Earned Tribute to Mrs. Silverman|url=https://newspapers.library.in.gov/cgi-bin/imageserver.pl?oid=JPOST19490603-01&getpdf=true|accessdate=29 December 2015|issue=Vol. 4, No 42 Indiana Edition|work=The National Jewish Post|date=3 June 1949|location=Indianapolis, Indiana|page=8}}</ref> Before her first birthday, her parents immigrated to New York and then when she was around ten years old, they moved to [[Providence, Rhode Island]].{{sfn|American Mothers Committee|1976|p=479}} She attended public grammar school and high school{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1973|p=480}} and, at sixteen years old, went to work as a bookkeeper for Archibald Silverman.<ref name="alternate name spelling" /> Archibald, also an immigrant, had begun his career as a designer of [[costume jewelry]].{{sfn|Browning|Hollander|Tec|2007|p=18}} Together with his brother, Charles, he established the Silverman Brothers jewelry company in Providence in 1897.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1459293141.html|title=The Stories of Her Life|first=Marcia|last=Litt|work=[[Washington Jewish Week]]|date=13 March 2008|accessdate=29 December 2015|subscription=yes}}</ref> After two years of working in the jewelry business, Camelhor agreed to marry her boss;<ref name="alternate name spelling" /> they wed in 1900.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1973|p=480}}

Archibald continued to work his way up and eventually became president of a bank and a philanthropist for Jewish causes.{{sfn|Browning|Hollander|Tec|2007|p=18}} Though Ida was the spokesperson and "presence" of the causes in which the couple were involved, Archibald fully supported her participation and gave his time, moral support, and monetary contributions to further their philanthropy.{{sfn|Foster|Horvitz|Cohen|1998|p=96}} He also understood and accepted that her work for others would always take precedence over her own household duties.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|p=115}}

==Career==
[[File:Ida Silverman and daughter 1925.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Ida Silverman and daughter 1925]]By age 20, Silverman had two children,{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1973|p=480}} and would soon have two more.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|p=115}} She was involved in the community of Providence and social betterment programs. She founded and served as president of the Ladies Auxiliary of the Jewish Orphanage of Rhode Island.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1973|p=480}} By 1906, she was involved in the American [[Zionist Movement]] and rose to the national position of vice president of the [[Hadassah Women's Zionist Organization of America]].<ref name="resignation Hadassah">{{cite news|title=Mrs. Archibald Silverman Resigns as Vice President of Hadassah|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3911777/the_wisconsin_jewish_chronicle/|accessdate=29 December 2015|work=The Wisconsin Jewish Chronicle|date=4 May 1928|location=Milwaukee, Wisconsin|page=2|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> Relief work during World War I awakened her to the broad variety of social needs and she became an advocate of health care, poverty relief, and finding a permanent solution for Jewish refugees.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Liber|first1=Libby|title=Women's Whirl|url=https://newspapers.library.in.gov/cgi-bin/imageserver.pl?oid=JPOST19460201-01&getpdf=true|accessdate=29 December 2015|issue=Vol. 14 No. 5 Indiana Edition|work=The National Jewish Post|date=1 February 1946|location=Indianapolis, Indiana|page=13}}</ref>  In 1915, Silverman founded the second Hadassah chapter in New England in Providence.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|p=112}} She was a "skilled propagandist", developing a wide following between 1915 and 1919, and was known as a vigorous leader and talented orator.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|p=116}}

Her first acknowledgement on the national level was her appointment in 1919 to honorary vice president of the [[American Jewish Congress]] (AJC). Traditionally, the AJC leadership were more focused on European Jews than worldwide outreach and were of the aristocratic, wealthy, [[Reform Judaism|Reform tradition]].{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|p=116}} By 1919 the organization had become more diverse and while not necessarily embracing the more radical aspects of Zionism, leaders allowed Zionist views to be expressed.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|p=117}} Silverman, as an honorary official, could use the status to her advantage: while not officially speaking for the organization, she tacitly had AJC endorsement and was able to parlay that into support from the masses for causes and monetary contributions from elites.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|p=118}}

===1920s===
In 1925 Silverman made her first trip to [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] and was able to use her experiences to gain speaking engagements in a variety of venues.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|p=119}} Throughout the remainder of the 1920s, Silverman served as vice president of the Zionist Organization of America and vice chair of the hospital building fund for the [[Hebrew University]]. In addition to her national organizational work, Silverman was vice president of the New England Zionist Region, the New England Conference of Hadassah, and an honorary president of the Hadassah Organization in Providence.<ref name="local, state, national">{{cite news|title=National Vice-president of Hadassah to Speak Here|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3911924/the_morning_herald/|accessdate=29 December 2015|work=The Morning Herald|date=12 December 1927|location=Uniontown, Pennsylvania|page=1|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}} and {{cite news|title=National Vice-president part2|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3911943/the_morning_herald/|accessdate=29 December 2015|work=The Morning Herald|date=12 December 1927|location=Uniontown, Pennsylvania|page=14|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> She is the only woman to have served as vice president of the Zionist Organization of America and the [[American Jewish Congress]].{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1973|p=480}}

[[File:Ida Silverman National Jewish Fund.jpg|thumb|300px|Ida Silverman National Jewish Fund]] Silverman was an outspoken proponent for Israeli statehood, traveling throughout the Americas and Europe advocating for a Jewish homeland.{{sfn|Goodwin|Smith|2004|p=xv}} She depicted the Jews who had resettled in Palestine as simple farmers, seeking an agrarian life to alleviate the hunger they had experienced elsewhere. Silverman stressed that the settlers' intent was not to industrialize and vie with the international powerhouse nations, but simply to provide for their basic needs.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|p=119}} Throughout 1927 and 1928, her itinerary included a speaking engagement in [[Savannah, Georgia]] with Sir [[Wyndham Deedes]], prior chief secretary of Palestine;{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|pp=120–121}} a tour of hospitals, clinics and public health programs in the Holy Land to determine how Hadassah could improve the health of the entire region, "without regard to race or creed";<ref name="local, state, national" /> and attendance at the World Zionist Congress in [[Basel, Switzerland]].{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|pp=120–121}} Silverman resigned from Hadassah in 1928 in a policy dispute<ref name="resignation Hadassah" /> over the high salaries being paid to administrators rather than using the funds for charitable works.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|pp=121–122}}

===1930s===
[[File:Ida Silverman 1938 2.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Silverman in 1938]]
Despite the [[Great Depression]], Silverman's travels expanded in the 1930s, when she began spending 6 months each year outside the U.S.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|p=124}} As early as 1932, land purchase programs to buy and settle refugees on permanent homes in Palestine were being pursued by Jewish organizations. Silverman not only supported the plans and raised funds for them, but she planted the first tree in the colony at Wady Havarith.<ref>{{cite news|title=Settling Jewish Ex-soldiers Who Fought in Palestine on Palestine Soil|url=http://www.jta.org/1932/06/09/archive/settling-jewish-ex-soldiers-who-fought-in-palestine-on-palestine-soil|accessdate=29 December 2015|publisher=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|date=June 9, 1932|location=New York, New York}}</ref> With [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]]'s rise to power, Silverman's pleas for a safe haven for Jews became more urgent{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|p=125}} and her first-hand reports from Germany, Austria, Hungary, Czechoslovakia, Lithuania, and Poland<ref name=travels>{{cite news|title=Mrs. Silverman to be Guest Speaker at JNF's David Ben-Gurion Dinner|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3912211/the_wisconsin_jewish_chronicle/|accessdate=29 December 2015|work=The Wisconsin Jewish Chronicle|date=28 December 1956|location=Milwaukee, Wisconsin|page=5|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> contained explicit accounts of conditions.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|p=126}} In 1938, Silverman was working with the Youth Aliyah Movement in conjunction with Hadassah in the U.S. to relocate 10,000 refugee children to Palestine. As a fund-raiser, Silverman's goal was to raise a quarter of a million dollars for resettlement and youth training in agricultural and vocational pursuits.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former Hadassah Officer to Speak at Rally Here|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3911762/the_evening_news/|accessdate=29 December 2015|work=The Evening News|date=13 December 1938|location=Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|page=4|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> In 1939, she ended her Polish tour studying the conditions and desperation,{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|p=126}} shortly before the [[German invasion of Poland|Polish invasion]],<ref name=travels /><ref name="london bombings">{{cite news|title=Tells of Atrocities Perpetrated on Jews|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3916643/tells_of_atrocities_perpetrated_on/|accessdate=29 December 2015|work=The Ottawa Journal|date=9 December 1942|location=Ottawa, Canada|page=7|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> but the effort was successful in relocating some 7,000 young people from Poland, Germany, Czechoslovakia, and Romania to Palestine before the end of 1940.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|p=126}}

===1940s===
Because riots had broken out in the late 1930s over British proposals to [[United Nations Partition Plan for Palestine|partition Palestine]],{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|p=126}} and U.S. diplomats including [[Sumner Welles]] proposed American alternatives,<ref name="Sosúa, Dominican Republic">{{cite news|last1=Lewis|first1=Ben|title=Between You and Me|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3915671/the_wisconsin_jewish_chronicle/|accessdate=29 December 2015|work=The Wisconsin Jewish Chronicle|date=5 December 1941|location=Milwaukee, Wisconsin|page=6|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Memories of the Forty-Niners |url=https://newspapers.library.in.gov/cgi-bin/imageserver.pl?oid=JPOST19410718-01&getpdf=true|accessdate=29 December 2015|issue=Vol. 10, No. 6 Indiana Edition|work=The National Jewish Post|date=18 July 1941|location=Indianapolis, Indiana|page=8}}</ref> Silverman embarked on several tours of South America and the Caribbean in the early 1940s to determine if, as an alternative to Palestinian resettlement, European Jews could be established in the [[Dominican Republic]], [[Peru]], or [[Uruguay]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sand|first1=Nathan|title=Report on Inter-American Conference in Baltimore, Nov. 23&ndash;24&ndash;25|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3915601/the_wisconsin_jewish_chronicle/|accessdate=29 December 2015|work=The Wisconsin Jewish Chronicle|date=5 December 1941|location=Milwaukee, Wisconsin|page=8|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> She reported on her findings at the Inter-American Conference in Baltimore, describing the alternatives as unfavorable and the attempt in the Dominican Republic, as a "failure".<ref name="Sosúa, Dominican Republic" /> She also wrote articles under the byline ''Mrs. Archibald Silverman'', urging the emigration of Jews to Palestine rather than to other places &ndash; such as a Jewish colony in [[Sosúa]], [[Dominican Republic]], promoted by the [[American Jewish Joint Distribution Committee]] in the early 1940s; a plan to settle Jews in the [[Kimberley (Western Australia)|Kimberley region]] of Australia; and another proposal for a Jewish colony in [[Paramaribo]], [[Suriname]]. Her articles were filled with vitriol against what she perceived as the "schemes" of Jewish organizers opposed to Zionism; in a 1948 article titled "The Surinam Nightmare", she "described 'diabolical plans' to abandon Jewish 'guinea pigs' to 'terrifying tropical diseases'". Eventually the alternative emigration plans were scrapped in the wake of the 1948 declaration of independence by the State of Israel.{{sfn|Rovner|2014|pp=213–215}}

[[File:Ida Silverman presents scroll.jpg|thumb|Ida Silverman presenting a scroll to Israeli Defense Minister [[Joseph Jacobsen (politician)|Joseph Jacobsen]]]]
After the Inter-American Conference in Baltimore, Silverman continued her travels in South America, and then obtained special permission to travel through England, Scotland, and Ireland to raise money. {{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1973|p=481}} Her collections were a resounding success, which she attributed to the acute understanding of homelessness experienced by British citizens who had been displaced during [[The Blitz|bombing raids]].<ref name="london bombings" /> Anticipating the war's end, Silverman increased efforts to buy land in Palestine,<ref>{{cite news|title=Zionists Launch Big Drive to Buy Refugees Land|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1943/01/25/page/15/article/zionists-launch-big-drive-to-buy-refugees-land|accessdate=30 December 2015|work=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=25 January 1943|location=Chicago, Illinois|page=15}}</ref> believing that if Jewish organizations owned land, when the Peace Conference occurred, bargaining would be in their favor.<ref>{{cite news|title=Palestine Only Haven, Declares Mrs. Silverman|url=http://jtn.stparchive.com/Archive/JTN/JTN11021942P08.php|accessdate=30 December 2015|work=The Jewish Transcript|date=2 November 1942|location=Seattle, Washington|page=8}}</ref>

As the war was ending in 1945, Silverman was on the road, traveling through all the countries of [[Central America]], in South America, New Zealand, Australia, and South Africa on fund-raising missions.<ref name="oceania and africa">{{cite news|title=JNF Will Hold State Conference Here, September 29|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3915200/the_wisconsin_jewish_chronicle/|accessdate=29 December 2015|work=The Wisconsin Jewish Chronicle|date=20 September 1946|location=Milwaukee, Wisconsin|page=1|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> Then in 1946, she was in Europe visiting refugee camps in Sweden and [[Allied-occupied Germany|Occupied Germany]], before returning to Palestine.<ref>{{cite news|title=US Zone Has 139,026 Displaced Jews|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3916799/the_wisconsin_jewish_chronicle/|accessdate=29 December 2015|work=The Wisconsin Jewish Chronicle|date=4 October 1946|location=Milwaukee, Wisconsin|page=1|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> By the end of the war, she had traveled 600,000 air-miles{{sfn|American Mothers Committee|1976|p=479}}<ref name="hotel and synagogues">{{cite news|last1=Silver|first1=Samuel|title=Silver Lining|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3915779/the_wisconsin_jewish_chronicle/|accessdate=29 December 2015|work=The Wisconsin Jewish Chronicle|date=28 October 1966|location=Milwaukee, Wisconsin|page=2|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> having visited every state in the United States, each province of Canada,<ref name=travels /> Mexico,<ref name="more travels">{{cite news|title=Will Be Speaker for Jewish Fund Appeal Meeting|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3917057/the_kingston_daily_freeman/|accessdate=29 December 2015|work=The Kingston Daily Freeman|date=29 March 1960|location=Kingston, New York|page=11|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> all of the countries in Central and South America,<ref name=travels /> the [[West Indies]], almost all of Western Europe,<ref name="more travels" /> parts of Eastern Europe,<ref name=travels /> Australia, New Zealand, Iran, Palestine, Morocco,<ref name="more travels" /> and South Africa.<ref name="oceania and africa" />

===1950s and 1960s===
[[File:Ida Silverman 1960.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Ida Silverman in 1960]]
After the State of Israel was established, Silverman recognized the diverse needs to build the nation and she and Archibald channeled funds into planting orchards, building the Sharon Hotel, and supplementing the Synagogue Centre Building Fund.<ref name="hotel and synagogues"/> The Sharon Hotel, built in Herzliya,{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1973|p=481}} on the [[Sharon Plain]], was part of an effort to build infrastructure<ref name="Sharon Plain">{{cite news|title=The Greatest Cause of All|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=z48cAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1WEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3023%2C6280292|accessdate=31 December 2015|work=The Canadian Jewish Chronicle|date=16 March 1928|location=Montreal, Canada}}</ref> and develop tourism sites to stimulate further growth.<ref name="hotel and synagogues" /> Silverman founded and served the board of the company which created the hotel.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1973|p=481}} In the [[Jezreel Valley]], she chaired a water development company and established a mixed-fruit orchard of around 70 acres of trees.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1973|p=481}} She also was involved in several projects in Rhode Island. In 1955 she founded and served as president of the Friends of [[Butler Hospital]] in an attempt to reopen the health center, which had been shut down.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1973|p=482}} They were successful in proving its benefit to the community and the hospital reopened.<ref name="more travels" /> In 1957, Silverman served as chair of the fundraising for the Rhode Island Association of Mental Health.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1973|p=482}} By the early-1960s, 33 [[synagogue]]s throughout Israel had been built through the synagogue fund.<ref name="more travels" /> During the two years she lived in Israel, she helped erect around 80 additional synagogues{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1980|p=127}} and by the time of Silverman's death, the number was over 100 synagogues in Israel and elsewhere.<ref name="Ida Silverman" />

===1970s===
In 1971, at the age of 89, Silverman [[aliyah|immigrated]] to Israel.{{sfn|American Mothers Committee|1976|p=480}} She died on 1 November 1973 in [[Herzliya]], Israel and was buried in the [[Mount of Olives Jewish Cemetery]] near [[Jerusalem]].{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1973|p=482}}

==Honors and awards==
In 1951 Silverman was honored as Jewish Mother of the Year{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1973|p=480}} by the [[Jewish National Fund]], which established a forest in Israel bearing her name.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mrs. Silverman Named Jewish Mother of 1951|url=https://newspapers.library.in.gov/cgi-bin/imageserver.pl?oid=JPOST19510525-01&getpdf=true|accessdate=29 December 2015|issue=Vol. 6, No. 39 Indiana Edition|work=The National Jewish Post|date=25 May 1951|location=Indianapolis, Indiana|page=8}}</ref> In 1953, a village in Israel, ''Nachlat Ida'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Mrs. A. Silverman, JNF Leader, to Address April 4 Meeting|url=https://newspapers.library.in.gov/cgi-bin/imageserver.pl?oid=JPOST19570329-01&getpdf=true|accessdate=29 December 2015|issue=Indiana Edition|work=The National Jewish Post|date=29 March 1957 |location=Indianapolis, Indiana|page=3}}</ref> was named in her honor to recognize her years of financial and moral support,<ref>{{cite news|title=Mrs. Archibald Silverman Honored on 70th Birthday|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3912027/the_wisconsin_jewish_chronicle/|accessdate=29 December 2015|work=The Wisconsin Jewish Chronicle|date=19 June 1953|location=Milwaukee, Wisconsin|page=9|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> and in 1954, she was honored as Rhode Island Mother of the Year.{{sfn|Browning|Hollander|Tec|2007|p=18}} She received an [[honorary doctorate]] from [[Rhode Island College]] in 1954 and one from [[Bryant University|Bryant College]] in 1960.<ref name="more travels" /> In 1964, she was awarded the [[AMIT|Mizrachi Women's Organization of America]]'s "Silver Medal" for having done the most to build Israel.{{sfn|Jewish Historical Notes|1973|p=481}}

Silverman and her husband (who had died in 1966{{sfn|American Mothers Committee|1976|p=480}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Archibald Silverman, Well-known U.S. Jewish Leader, Dead; Was 86|url=http://www.jta.org/1966/09/21/archive/archibald-silverman-well-known-u-s-jewish-leader-dead-was-86|accessdate=29 December 2015|publisher=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|date=September 21, 1966|location=New York, New York}}</ref>) were jointly inducted into the [[Rhode Island Heritage Hall of Fame Women Inductees|Rhode Island Heritage Hall of Fame]] in 1971.<ref name="Ida Silverman">{{cite web|title=Ida Silverman|url=http://www.riheritagehalloffame.org/inductees_detail.cfm?crit=det&iid=275|publisher=Rhode Island Heritage Hall of Fame|accessdate=27 December 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151227195319/http://www.riheritagehalloffame.org/inductees_detail.cfm?crit=det&iid=292|archivedate=27 December 2015|location=Riverside, Rhode Island}}</ref>

