{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}} {{Infobox football biography | name= Matt Tees | image = | fullname = Matthew Tees<ref>{{Hugman|19382|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1939|10|13|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Johnstone]], Scotland | height = 6 ft 4 in | currentclub = | clubnumber = | position = [[Forward (football)|Forward]] | youthyears1 = 1957 | youthclubs1 = Penaleen Athletic | youthyears2 = 1957&ndash;1960 | youthclubs2 = [[Cambuslang Rangers]] | years1 = 1960 | years2 = 1960&ndash;1963 | years3 = 1963&ndash;1967 | years4 = 1967&ndash;1969 | years5 = 1969&ndash;1971 | years6 = 1971&ndash;1973 | years7 = 1973&ndash;1974 | years8 = 1974&ndash;1975 | clubs1 = [[Forfar Athletic F.C.|Forfar Athletic]] (trialist) | clubs2 = [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrieonians]] | clubs3 = [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] | clubs4 = [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] | clubs5 = [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] | clubs6 = [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] | clubs7 = [[Boston United F.C.|Boston United]] | clubs8 = Greyhound | caps1 = 1 | caps2 = 43 | caps3 = 113 | caps4 = 89 | caps5 = 35 | caps6 = 83 | goals1 = 1 | goals2 = 12 | goals3 = 51 | goals4 = 32 | goals5 = 13 | goals6 = 42 | totalcaps = 364 | totalgoals= 151 }} '''Matt Tees''' (born 13 October 1939) is a Scottish former [[association football|football]] player.
Originally a [[machinist]] at a [[carpet]] factory, he was discovered while playing for local leagues in [[Scotland]] with [[Cambuslang Rangers]]. After a spell with [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrie]], he played for [[Grimsby Town]] (two spells), [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] and [[Luton Town]] before ending his career with [[Boston United]] in the [[Northern Premier League]].
==Career== After beginning his career in the local leagues in [[Scotland]] with [[Cambuslang Rangers]] before joining professional [[Association football|football]] with [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrie]]. He then joined [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]], [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]], [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] and back to [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]], during his second spell at Grimsby, Tees was part of the [[1971–72 in English football|1971–72]] team that won the [[Football League Fourth Division|Division Four]] title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.football.co.uk/snapshot_tables/1971_1972/2/may/grimsby_town/index.shtml |title=Historical league tables |publisher=Stats.football.co.uk |date= |accessdate=24 August 2012}}</ref><ref name="A sea of 23,000 fans"/>
A 2017 [[BBC]] documentary on [[dementia]] among retired footbllers included a visit to Tees' family home, where it was confirmed he had an advanced stage of the condition; it was suggested that the cause may be the high number of times he headed the ball during his playing career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2017/11/12/alan-shearer-dementia-football-review-impassioned-thoughtful1/|title=Alan Shearer: Dementia, Football and Me review – an impassioned and thoughtful documentary |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=12 November 2017|accessdate=3 January 2018}}</ref>
==Honours== ===Club=== ;Grimsby Town *[[Football League Fourth Division|Division Four]] '''Champions (1):''' [[1971–72 in English football|1971–72]]<ref name="A sea of 23,000 fans">{{cite news |url=http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/sea-23-000-fans-roared-McMenemy-s-champions-71/story-11548372-detail/story.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505070039/http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/sea-23-000-fans-roared-McMenemy-s-champions-71/story-11548372-detail/story.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=5 May 2013 |newspaper=Grimsby Telegraph |title=A sea of 23,000 fans roared on McMenemy's champions of 71 |date=15 May 2010 |accessdate=24 August 2012 }}</ref>
