{{Use Canadian English|date=October 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}} {{Infobox musical artist | name = Rachel Zeffira | background = solo_singer | image = | caption = | birth_name = Rachel Santesso | birth_date = | birth_place = | genre = | occupation = Vocalist, musician, singer-songwriter, conductor, choral arranger | years_active = | instrument = [[Singing|Vocals]], [[piano]], [[keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[oboe]], [[cor anglais]], [[violin]], [[viola]], [[percussion instrument|percussion]] | label = | associated_acts = [[Cat's Eyes]], Capital Children's Choir }}
'''Rachel Zeffira''' (born '''Rachel Santesso''') is a [[Canadian]] [[soprano]], composer and multi-instrumentalist currently based in [[London]], [[England]]. She is also one half of the duo [[Cat's Eyes]], the other being [[Faris Badwan]] of [[the Horrors]].<ref>Tucker, Rebecca. [http://arts.nationalpost.com/2011/01/24/canadian-opera-singer-british-rock-star-hook-up-at-the-vatican/ "Canadian opera singer, British rock star hook up at the Vatican"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120701170921/http://arts.nationalpost.com/2011/01/24/canadian-opera-singer-british-rock-star-hook-up-at-the-vatican/ |date=1 July 2012 }}. ''[[National Post]]''. 24 January 2011.</ref>
==History== ===Early life=== Zeffira studied voice and organ at the Conservatorio Di Musica F.E. Dall'Abaco di [[Verona]] and [[oboe]] at the [[University of Victoria]] in [[Canada]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = About The Choir|url = http://www.capitalchoir.com/about/|website = Capital Children's Choir|accessdate = 2016-01-10}}</ref> She is a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Arts]], and in 2001, founded the [[Capital Children's Choir]], which she also directs.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nadine Cheung |url=http://popcrush.com/lady-gaga-capital-childrens-choir-judas-cover/ |title=Lady Gaga Approves of Capital Children’s Choir’s Haunting ‘Judas’ Cover |publisher=Popcrush.com |date=16 July 2011 |accessdate=2016-01-08}}</ref> Several videos of the choir's covers of contemporary songs such as "Chances" and "Untrust Us" received media attention and went viral.<ref>{{cite web|author=Melissa Locker |url=http://time.com/4078265/choir-school-kids-the-strokes-cover |title=Capital Children’s Choir Covers The Strokes "Chances" |publisher=Time.com |date=2015-10-19 |accessdate=2016-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Nme.Com |url=http://www.nme.com/news/crystal-castles/71736 |title=London children's choir covers Crystal Castles' 'Untrust Us' – watch |publisher=Nme.Com |date=2013-07-30 |accessdate=2016-01-08}}</ref> Zeffira released several albums with the Capital Children's Choir, and in 2015, the choir performed on the soundtrack for the film ''[[Pan (2015 film)|Pan]]''. As a soprano, she released two albums, ''The Songs of Louis Vierne'' (2005) and ''The Sacred Heart of Nino Rota'' (2007).
Zeffira taught briefly at a primary school in [[London]], where she taught a young [[Lily Allen]], who has credited Zeffira as a [[mentor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/video-youth-choir-has-online-hit-with-lily-allen-song-6778573.html |title=VIDEO: Youth choir has online hit with Lily Allen song &#124; News &#124; London Evening Standard |publisher=Standard.co.uk |date=2009-07-16 |accessdate=2016-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2008/sep/13/celebrity.television |title=What were today's celebrities like as children? &#124; Life and style |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2016-01-08}}</ref>
===Cat's Eyes=== While Zeffira was working as an opera singer and classical musician, she met Badwan. The two friends began to write songs together and formed the band Cat's Eyes. The duo made their first public appearance at the [[Holy See|Vatican]],<ref>Rachel Zeffira's Vatican connections/MTV [http://www.mtvhive.com/2013/03/12/rachel-zeffira-interview-the-deserters/] Retrieved 25 September 2013</ref> where they performed one of their songs as a mass setting, with [[church organ]] and choir during a service at [[St. Peter's Basilica]]. Cat's Eyes were signed by [[Polydor]] in 2010 and released their [[Cat's Eyes (album)|eponymous debut album]] in April 2011. The album received positive press and critical acclaim.<ref>Metacritic 18 reviews [http://www.metacritic.com/music/cats-eyes/cats-eyes] Retrieved 25 September 2013</ref> During this time, Zeffira appeared in ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' magazine,<ref>Vogue artist of the week [http://www.vogue.com/culture/article/artist-of-the-week-cats-eyes-rachel-zeffira/#1] Retrieved 20 August 2012</ref> and was shot by the photographer [[Rankin (photographer)|Rankin]]<ref>Dazed and Confused magazine cover with Bobby Gillespie [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gSHib-Lv2UA] Retrieved 5 December 2013</ref> for the cover of ''[[Dazed & Confused (magazine)|Dazed & Confused]]'' alongside [[Bobby Gillespie]] of [[Primal Scream]].
===Solo work=== Zeffira's first solo album, ''The Deserters'', was released 10 December 2012 on RAF Records in Europe and [[Paper Bag Records]] in North America. The title track was chosen for the trailer to the final season of the TV program ''[[Skins (North American TV series)|Skins]]''.<ref>Rachel Zeffira for Skins [http://www.umusicpub.co.uk/en-GB/Artists/R/Rachel-Zeffira.aspx#/en-GB/FilmAndTv/2013/Jun/Rachel-Zeffira-for-Skins-Season-7-Trailer.aspx] Retrieved 25 September 2013</ref> Zeffira received positive press for the debut<ref>BBC album review [https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/zjrj] Retrieved 14 November 2012</ref> <ref>The Observer album review [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/dec/09/rachel-zeffira-the-deserters-review] Retrieved 14 November 2012</ref> and the album was listed in ''[[The Times]]'' Top 5 albums of 2012 in spite of its late release date.<ref>The Times, 21 Dec.2012</ref>
Zeffira also received critical praise for her live performances.<ref>Times live review [http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/music/livereviews/article3735980.ece] Retrieved 25 May 2013</ref><ref>The Independent live review [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/rachel-zeffira-st-andrews-holborn-london-8221770.html] Retrieved 14 November 2012</ref> In June 2013. she was the opening act for [[Glastonbury Festival 2013]].<ref>Glastonbury's opening act [https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2013/jun/27/new-music-rachel-zeffira-because] Retrieved 25 August 2013</ref>
In April 2013, Zeffira made her American radio debut on [[NPR]]'s ''[[All Things Considered]]'',<ref>NPR All Things Considered [https://www.npr.org/2013/04/16/177471795/rachel-zeffira-an-opera-deserter-embraces-dreamy-pop] Retrieved 25 August 2013</ref> and later made her Canadian radio debut with a live session on [[CBC Radio One]] show ''[[Q (radio show)|Q]]'' with [[Jian Ghomeshi]]<ref>Q with Jian Ghomeshi [http://www.cbc.ca/q/blog/2013/07/05/rachel-zeffiras-surprising-life-and-art/] Retrieved 5 December 2013</ref>
===Film score compositions=== Zeffira is listed as composer, arranger, orchestrator, conductor, musician and soprano on the Cat's Eyes soundtrack (released in February 2015) for the 2014 film ''[[The Duke of Burgundy]]'', directed by [[Peter Strickland (director)|Peter Strickland]]. The score received positive press and majority 5-star reviews.<ref>Times review [http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/music/albumreviews/article4345238.ece] Retrieved 11 Nov 2015</ref><ref>The Guardian review [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/feb/12/cats-eyes-the-duke-of-burgundy-soundtrack-review] Retrieved 11 Nov 2015</ref> On 7 November 2015, it was announced that Zeffira and Badwan had won the [[European Film Award for Best Composer]].<ref>Hollywood Reporter [http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/efa-tech-honors-goodnight-mommy-834790] Retrieved 11 Nov 2015</ref>
